      <hedline>
        <hl1>In the Fray Of Education</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lois Taylor letter on June 11 article hold it is trivial for Connecticut educators to concern themselves with ethnic breakdown of teaching staff (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>With Connecticut schools struggling to provide an adequate, let alone excellent, education, it seems trivial to concern ourselves with the ethnic breakdown of the teaching staff (''White Faces at the Blackboard,'' June 11).</p>
        <p>Surely all students, white and minority, are entitled to the best instructors available, regardless of how this might affect the desired diversity.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>With Connecticut schools struggling to provide an adequate, let alone excellent, education, it seems trivial to concern ourselves with the ethnic breakdown of the teaching staff (''White Faces at the Blackboard,'' June 11).</p>
        <p>Surely all students, white and minority, are entitled to the best instructors available, regardless of how this might affect the desired diversity.</p>
        <p>Black students and black parents who want the best education for their children will surely consider the quality of the classroom experience ahead of the ethnic classification of the teacher.</p>
        <p>Teachers are too important to be hired on any basis other than credentials and suitability for the job.</p>
        <p>LOIS TAYLOR  Old Greenwich</p>
      </block>
